\f3\i Known issues
\f1\i0 :\
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\tx7200\li400\fi-140\ql\qnatural
\cf0 - There is a conflict between MacCvsX and CWCVS: CWCVS still insists on locking the files after checkout or commit, whereas MacCvsX now uses the underlying file system permissions to make files read-only. This means that while you can use CWCVS generally, you'll run into trouble when you let CWCVS commit a file or checkout files, since cvsgui just doesn't expect the files to be locked and can't work with them afterwards... unfortunately, this issue must be resolved in CWCVS.\
- When Python is installed, you'll see a bunch of Python error messages at startup; those are because the _tkinter python module can't be properly initialized because the Python framework is not properly configured for Tk; many macros should work nonetheless.\
- While MacCvsX runs on Mac OS X 10.1, the cvsgui tool in this distribution currently refuses to run, since it attempts to load Kerberos framework version 5.0.0, but 10.1 only provides version 1.0.0 which apparently is not compatible. You may be able to recompile the cvsgui tool on Mac OS X 10.1 and replace the tool inside the application package with the version built on 10.1... The effect of the tool not running is that you can't perform any cvs operations on 10.1 :(\
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\tx7200\ql\qnatural
\cf0 \
- 3.3a1\
  + This is the first alpha release of the 3.3 unstable development cycle.\
  + A lot of things are new, mainly MacCvsX now relies on an external command line which spawns the cvs process (cvsgui).\
  + MacCvsX is using the real ssh (/usr/bin/ssh). In order to use ssh with MacCvsX, you should have your ssh keys all set-up so the connection with cvs server doesn't prompt for a password (MacCvs doesn't have an interactive TTY).\
  + Python support requires MachoPython version 2.3 or higher (currently in alpha stage).\
